title: SFH on human swine flu
content_text:
p>
Following is the transcript of remarks made by the Secretary for Food and 
Health, Dr York Chow, after attending a radio programme today (May 2): Reporter: Since the case has been imported to Hong Kong, would you ask 
airline carriers to urge their flight attendants to wear masks? Secretary for Food and Health: First of all, we have informed all the 
airlines coming to Hong Kong that they should be vigilant in noticing any 
passengers who might have symptoms of flu. If they do, they need to give

passengers who might have symptoms of flu. If they do, they need to give 
face mask to him or her and also the neighbouring passengers as well. We 
also advise that if that is the case, the crew should also wear mask when 
serving those passengers. It is more important for each airline to ensure 
that each airplane would carry sufficient protective gears for their staff 
as well as the necessary antiseptics and so on for their passengers. So, it 
is something that I think is important. And the staff actually feels unwell

is something that I think is important. And the staff actually feels unwell 
and uncomfortable for not wearing a mask, I think they should be more 
flexible and allow them to wear. Reporter: (Schools to resume on Monday?) Secretary for Food and Health: The Emergency Response Level Steering 
Committee will meet again this afternoon. We will assess the situation with 
the Education Bureau to decide whether there are additional measures that 
need to be taken and contingency plans to be arranged. Since schools will be 
resumed on Monday, the Education Bureau perhaps would need to make a very

resumed on Monday, the Education Bureau perhaps would need to make a very 
clear instruction tomorrow on whether the schools will be resumed or not. If 
the situation is not going to be worsen, I would advise to resume school. 
But it is important for parents and also students to ensure that they are 
healthy if they are going to school. If they have any symptoms of flu or 
upper respiratory infection, they should stay at home. Reporter: (inaudible) Secretary for Food and Health: If we find that any more infection in other

places, we will look at the situation to decide whether we need to isolate 
the place or quarantine those contacts. At the moment, because this is the 
first case, we thought that this is also an appropriate time for us to 
contain this infection before it spreads further. If the situation is going 
to spread further, just like some of the other cities in Mexico and also the 
United States, then our next battle line will shift to the community and 
also to the hospitals. The reason why we quarantine people now is not only

also to the hospitals. The reason why we quarantine people now is not only 
for their own safety, but also to have a clearer understanding of what 
prophylactic anti-virus can actually have. If prophylactic is going to 
happen, perhaps in future cases, we might not actually need to have a place 
for quarantine but just the prophylactic, the so-called home quarantine will 
be sufficient. I cannot make that decision at the moment, we need to have 
more information and experience in this virus before we can do that. (Please also refer to the
more information and experience in this virus before we can do that. (Please also refer to the Chinese session of the transcript)
